  "target_response": {
    "text": "Very fixable — feeling wired after a hard evening session is the normal tail of exercise arousal: elevated adrenaline and body temperature take a while to come down, and last night that cost you, with sleep at 6.7 hours versus your usual 7.4. The rest of your data is steady — recovery at 62% and resting heart rate of 62 bpm near your baseline of about 60 bpm — so this is a scheduling problem, not a health one. Practical levers: finish hard sessions earlier when you can, and when you can't, build a deliberate wind-down — cool shower, dim lights, a light carb-containing snack, no screens in bed. Keep caffeine to the morning on training days. One boundary note: post-training buzz that fades once you're asleep is benign, while a heart still pounding or racing hours later at rest is worth mentioning to a doctor. Yours reads as the ordinary kind.",
